  17:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h **** 
  18:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h **** /** \class Stride
  19:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  * \ingroup Core_Module
  20:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  *
  21:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  * \brief Holds strides information for Map
  22:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  *
  23:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  * This class holds the strides information for mapping arrays with strides with class Map.
  24:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  *
  25:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  * It holds two values: the inner stride and the outer stride.
  26:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  *
  27:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  * The inner stride is the pointer increment between two consecutive entries within a given row of 
  28:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  * row-major matrix or within a given column of a column-major matrix.
  29:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  *
  30:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  * The outer stride is the pointer increment between two consecutive rows of a row-major matrix or
  31:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  * between two consecutive columns of a column-major matrix.
  32:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  *
  33:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  * These two values can be passed either at compile-time as template parameters, or at runtime as
  34:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  * arguments to the constructor.
  35:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  *
  36:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  * Indeed, this class takes two template parameters:
  37:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  *  \tparam OuterStrideAtCompileTime_ the outer stride, or Dynamic if you want to specify it at run
  38:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  *  \tparam InnerStrideAtCompileTime_ the inner stride, or Dynamic if you want to specify it at run
  39:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  *
  40:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  * Here is an example:
  41:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  * \include Map_general_stride.cpp
  42:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  * Output: \verbinclude Map_general_stride.out
  43:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  *
  44:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  * Both strides can be negative. However, a negative stride of -1 cannot be specified at compile ti
ARM GAS  C:\Users\vinok\AppData\Local\Temp\ccn61esS.s 			page 76


  45:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  * because of the ambiguity with Dynamic which is defined to -1 (historically, negative strides wer
  46:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  * not allowed).
  47:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  *
  48:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  * Note that for compile-time vectors (ColsAtCompileTime==1 or RowsAtCompile==1),
  49:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  * the inner stride is the pointer increment between two consecutive elements,
  50:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  * regardless of storage layout.
  51:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  *
  52:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  * \sa class InnerStride, class OuterStride, \ref TopicStorageOrders
  53:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h ****  */
  54:../VCOM-G1/GuitarPedal/eigen/Eigen/src/Core/Stride.h **** template <int OuterStrideAtCompileTime_, int InnerStrideAtCompileTime_>
